<emphasis id="018BFD68401D5F36FBD9FE6F4BC93998" box="[1067,1197,485,506]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="277">tacanaense’</emphasis>
is descriptive of the name of the volcano Tacaná where this species was first reared.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A401D5F36FCD4FDDA4AE23C50" blockId="10.[806,1422,592,1074]" pageId="10" pageNumber="277">
<emphasis id="018BFD68401D5F36FCD4FDDA4C8D3A07" box="[806,1001,592,613]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="277">Taxonomic notes:</emphasis>
In general, appearance and structure of the male genitalia the adult of 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF9401D5F36FB2BFDE54A173AE6" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock" authorityYear="2004" box="[1241,1395,623,644]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="277" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tacanaense">
<emphasis id="018BFD68401D5F36FB2BFDE54A173AE6" box="[1241,1395,623,644]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="277">C. tacanaense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF9401D5F36FC68FD074B7F3AC0" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[922,1051,653,674]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="277" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gelenitae">
<emphasis id="018BFD68401D5F36FC68FD074B7F3AC0" box="[922,1051,653,674]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="277">C. gelenitae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. They are the only 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF9401D5F36FB06FD074A333AC0" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[1268,1367,653,674]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="277" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oscillans">
<emphasis id="018BFD68401D5F36FB06FD074A333AC0" box="[1268,1367,653,674]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="277">oscillans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup species with complete black vittae that extend across the gena from the lower eye margin to the mouthedge. They also have pairs of large, yellow spots on the abdomen with complete black margins to tergites 2–4. However, 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF9401D5F36FBA8FCAD4B903B5E" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock" authorityYear="2004" box="[1114,1268,807,828]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="277" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tacanaense">
<emphasis id="018BFD68401D5F36FBA8FCAD4B903B5E" box="[1114,1268,807,828]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="277">C. tacanaense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF9401D5F36FCD4FCCF4CC33B38" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[806,935,837,858]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="277" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gelenitae">
<emphasis id="018BFD68401D5F36FCD4FCCF4CC33B38" box="[806,935,837,858]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="277">C. gelenitae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a dark, not a yellow, mesonotum, and in lacking lateral projections to the hypandrium. It is unique among tank group species in having a male with black eye hairs. In all other species the eye hairs are either yellow or orange. The early stages of 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF9401D5F36FC6BFC554B503B96" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock" authorityYear="2004" box="[921,1076,991,1012]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="277" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tacanaense">
<emphasis id="018BFD68401D5F36FC6BFC554B503B96" box="[921,1076,991,1012]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="277">C. tacanaense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are readily distinguished by the thick, upright, dorsal vestiture, and the underside of the third pair of lappets setulate only at the base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A401D5F36FCD4FBC04AEB3CDE" blockId="10.[806,1423,1098,1212]" pageId="10" pageNumber="277">
<emphasis id="018BFD68401D5F36FCD4FBC04CE53C3D" box="[806,897,1098,1119]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="277">Biology:</emphasis>
Adults were reared from larvae in water tanks of small-sized bromeliads (
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF9401D5F36FB53FBE24A593C1C" box="[1185,1341,1128,1150]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="277" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Bromeliaceae</taxonomicName>
) growing on exposed rocks, cliff-faces, and under storey trees, and are known only from 
<collectingRegion id="F13BEF98401D5F36FB78FB2C4A493CD9" box="[1162,1325,1190,1212]" country="Mexico" name="Chiapas" pageId="10" pageNumber="277">Chiapas State</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="4BE861EA401D5F36FAC5FB2C4AEE3CDE" box="[1335,1418,1190,1212]" name="Mexico" pageId="10" pageNumber="277">Mexico</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
